MJP - 03/25/2026 MJP - 03/25/2026
1 (5) It is the intent of the Legislature that all money in the fund
2 shall be appropriated each fiscal year for the purposes that are
3 described in section 8 of this act.
4 Sec. 8. Subject to applicable federal and state law, money in the
5 Infrastructure Development Investment Program Fund may be used to:
6 (1) Provide any financial assistance to any eligible entity for any
7 eligible project;
8 (2) Establish reserves, capitalized interest, credit enhancement,
9 and pooled financing structures that strengthen the credit capacity of
10 the investment program;
11 (3) Pay reasonable administrative costs of the investment program,
12 including portfolio monitoring and collection; and
13 (4) Refinance or obtain interim financing used for any eligible
14 cost.
15 Sec. 9. (1) For administration of the investment program, the
16 commission may establish any:
17 (a) Federal, state, or local account or subaccount within the
18 investment program that is necessary to meet any applicable federal or
19 state law requirement;
20 (b) Bond-related account or subaccount within the investment program
21 that is necessary to meet any applicable federal or state law
22 requirement; or
23 (c) Account within the investment program that the commission
24 determines is necessary or desirable to implement the Infrastructure
25 Development Investment Program Act.
26 (2) The investment program shall consist of the following account
27 structure:
28 (a) Federal accounts: Separate accounts established for federal
29 highway, transit, rail, and rural project funds;
30 (b) State and local accounts: Separate accounts for state and local
31 transportation funds; and
-5-

ER159 ER159
LB1126 LB1126
MJP - 03/25/2026 MJP - 03/25/2026
1 (c) Administrative accounts: Separate accounts to be used by the
2 department for the cost of administering the investment program.
3 (3) The investment program shall comply with all applicable federal
4 laws and regulations prohibiting the commingling of certain federal funds
5 deposited in the investment program.
6 (4) Money in each account shall be tracked and used consistent with
7 the legal requirements of the source of such money.
8 Sec. 10. The investment program may make any contract and execute
9 any instrument that is necessary or convenient to provide financial
10 assistance, including any:
11 (1) Loan agreement, trust indenture, intercept agreement, or
12 reimbursement agreement;
13 (2) Acceptance of a pledge of project revenue, special assessment,
14 user fee, tax increment, or other legally available revenue;
15 (3) Requirement or funding of any reserve fund to secure repayment;
16 or
17 (4) Participation in any pooled financing or senior-subordinate
18 structure.
19 Sec. 11. (1) Any political subdivision may apply to the department
20 for a loan from the investment program on a form prescribed by the
21 department.
22 (2) The terms of a duly executed loan or assistance contract are
23 binding on the borrower, and the borrower shall unconditionally repay
24 from pledged sources.
25 Sec. 12. If a borrower of a loan from the investment program fails
26 to comply with any contract term related to such loan or fails to make
27 any payment when due, the investment program may:
28 (1) Pursue any legal or equitable remedy;
29 (2) Request that the Legislature reduce any appropriation to such
30 borrower by the amount that is owed to the investment program and
31 appropriate such amount to the investment program. The money for any such
-6-

ER159 ER159
LB1126 LB1126
MJP - 03/25/2026 MJP - 03/25/2026
1 appropriation to the investment program shall be transferred into the
2 Infrastructure Development Investment Program Fund and used to pay the
3 outstanding debt of such borrower; and
4 (3) Draw on any pledged reserve or credit facility that is securing
5 the obligation.
6 Sec. 13. The investment program shall maintain accounts in
7 accordance with generally accepted accounting principles and applicable
8 federal requirements, subject to annual independent audit.
9 Sec. 14. An obligation of the investment program is a special,
10 limited obligation that is payable solely from the revenue and assets of
11 the investment program and shall not constitute a pledge of the full
12 faith and credit of the State of Nebraska unless expressly authorized by
13 separate statute.
14 Sec. 15. (1) The investment program may provide financial
15 assistance to any eligible entity for any eligible project. Such
16 financial assistance may be in any lawful form, including any loan, loan
17 guarantee, line of credit, letter of credit, lease, lease-purchase
18 agreement, interest-rate subsidy, or credit enhancement, or any other
19 financing instrument that is approved by the commission.
20 (2)(a) All financial assistance provided by the investment program
21 shall be evidenced by a financing agreement that sets forth the principal
22 amount, interest rate, repayment schedule, security provisions,
23 covenants, and remedies upon default.
24 (b) The commission shall establish:
25 (i) Standardized documents for financial assistance that is provided
26 by the investment program; and
27 (ii) Credit criteria that will be applied when the investment
28 program is deciding to provide financial assistance in order to ensure
29 consistency, transparency, and fiscal integrity.
30 (3) Interest rates shall be set by the commission, within the
31 limitations of section 45-101.03, to reflect project risk, market
-7-

ER159 ER159
LB1126 LB1126
MJP - 03/25/2026 MJP - 03/25/2026
1 conditions, term length, and creditworthiness, and may include subsidies
2 for projects of statewide significance or in economically distressed
3 areas.
4 (4) The commission may charge an application fee for providing
5 financial assistance from the investment program. Such fee shall not
6 exceed one thousand dollars.
7 Sec. 16. (1) The maturity for any financial assistance that is
8 provided under the Infrastructure Development Investment Program Act
9 shall not exceed the lesser of the useful life of the financed asset or
10 thirty years, unless federal law allows a longer term or the commission
11 determines a longer term pursuant to state law.
12 (2) At the discretion of the commission, the repayment of any
13 financial assistance that is provided under the Infrastructure
14 Development Investment Program Act shall begin after completion of the
15 project or upon the generation of revenue from the project.
16 (3) The borrower of any financial assistance that is provided under
17 the Infrastructure Development Investment Program Act may prepay any
18 required payment for such financial assistance. No penalty is permitted
19 for such prepayment unless provided for by a bond covenant.
20 Sec. 17. (1) Financial assistance that is provided under the
21 Infrastructure Development Investment Program Act shall be secured by the
22 pledge of revenue from the project or system, any legally available
23 source, or any collateral required by the commission.
24 (2) The commission may require any reserve, intercept of any state
25 aid allocation, guarantee, or letter of credit to secure repayment.
26 (3) A public borrower may pledge revenue or credit only to the
27 extent permitted by state law and by ordinance or resolution of a
28 political subdivision.
29 Sec. 18. (1) The investment program may subordinate its lien to
30 senior debt if the commission determines that such subordination is
31 necessary to finance the project and is consistent with any bond
-8-

ER159 ER159
LB1126 LB1126
MJP - 03/25/2026 MJP - 03/25/2026
1 covenant.
2 (2) The investment program may extend, defer, capitalize, or
3 restructure repayments to preserve project viability or to mitigate
4 financial hardship, subject to federal requirements and the approval of
5 the commission.
6 Sec. 19. In the event of a default by a borrower under the
7 Infrastructure Development Investment Program Act, the investment program
8 may pursue any lawful remedy, including acceleration, set-off, intercept
9 of state aid that is otherwise due to the borrower, or transfer of
10 collateral, consistent with constitutional and federal limitations.
11 Sec. 20. (1) The investment program may provide financial
12 assistance to an eligible entity to pay for all or part of the eligible
13 cost of an eligible project. The investment program may require the
14 eligible entity to enter into a financing agreement in connection with
15 its financial assistance obligation.
16 (2) The commission shall determine the form and content of such
17 financing agreement and financial assistance obligations, including the
18 term and rate or rates of interest on a financing agreement.
19 (3) The terms and conditions of financial assistance from any
20 federal account shall comply with applicable federal requirements.
21 Sec. 21. The commission shall prioritize the approval of
22 applications for financial assistance based on objective criteria,
23 including, but not limited to:
24 (1) Economic impact and job creation;
25 (2) Safety and system resilience benefits;
26 (3) Readiness and financial feasibility;
27 (4) Public benefit;
28 (5) Consistency with statewide transportation goals;
29 (6) Leverage of private capital or money that is not provided by the
30 State of Nebraska;
31 (7) Local support of the project; and
-9-

ER159 ER159
